==> TOPIC:  USE OF PHOTOS

From:  Deirdre' Straughan <deirdres@tiscalinet.it>

Years ago I read about a professional who was very successful in
finding business via CompuServe and well-liked by his clients, until
a picture of him was published in the CompuServe print magazine, to
illustrate a piece on CompuServe success stories. Then business
dropped off sharply. His clients hadn't realized he was
African-American, and some of them evidently had a problem with
that. A sad and discouraging illustration of (some) human nature.
Sometimes you are better off to let your words and skills speak for
you, avoiding whatever prejudices someone may bring to a photo.

We all form mental pictures of who we're dealing with, even when
these are very imaginatively based only on impressions from text and
assumptions about names. Many people in the world don't know what
sort of name Deirdre is, and in the US Adrian is a female name. So
myself and my employee Adrian, both active online, were often amused
by Americans assuming he was female, and others assuming (purely on
the basis of my technical expertise) that I was male. It became one
of the standing jokes in the company.

Deirdré Straughan
http://web.newsguy.com/deirdre/

Comment? mailto:icontent@adventive.com


